  doi = {10.1093/mnras/stab674},
  abstract = {We present a panchromatic study of 11 (sub-)millimetre selected DSFGs with spectroscopically confirmed redshift (\$1.5{$<$} z\_\{\textbackslash rm spec\}{$<$}3\$) in the GOODS-S field, with the aim of constraining their astrophysical properties (e.g., age, stellar mass, dust and gas content) and characterizing their role in the context of galaxy evolution. The multi-wavelength coverage of GOODS-S, from X-rays to radio band, allow us to model galaxy SED by using CIGALE with a novel approach, based on a physical motivated modelling of stellar light attenuation by dust. Median stellar mass (\$\textbackslash simeq6.5\textbackslash times10\^\{10\}\$ M\$\_\textbackslash odot\$) and SFR (\$\textbackslash simeq241\$ M\$\_\textbackslash odot\$ yr\$\^\{-1\}\$) are consistent with galaxy main-sequence at \$z\textbackslash sim2\$. The galaxies are experiencing an intense and dusty burst of star formation (median L\$\_\{\textbackslash rm IR\}\textbackslash simeq2\textbackslash times10\^\{12\}\$ L\$\_\textbackslash odot\$), with a median age of \$750\$ Myr. The high median content of interstellar dust (M\$\_\{\textbackslash rm dust\}\textbackslash simeq5\textbackslash times10\^8\$ M\$\_\textbackslash odot\$) suggests a rapid enrichment of the ISM (on timescales \$\textbackslash sim10\^8\$ yr). We derived galaxy total and molecular gas content from CO spectroscopy and/or Rayleigh-Jeans dust continuum (\$10\^\{10\}\textbackslash lesssim\$ M\$\_\{\textbackslash rm gas\}/\$M\$\_\textbackslash odot\textbackslash lesssim10\^\{11\}\$), depleted over a typical timescale \$\textbackslash tau\_\{\textbackslash rm depl\}\textbackslash sim200\$ Myr. X-ray and radio luminosities suggest that most of the galaxies hosts an accreting radio silent/quiet SMBH. This evidence, along with their compact multi-wavelength sizes (median r\$\_\{\textbackslash rm ALMA\}\textbackslash sim\$ r\$\_\{\textbackslash rm VLA\}=1.8\$ kpc, r\$\_\{\textbackslash rm HST\}=2.3\$ kpc) measured from high-resolution imaging (\$\textbackslash theta\_\{\textbackslash rm res\}\textbackslash lesssim\$ 1 arcsec), indicates these objects as the high-z star-forming counterparts of massive quiescent galaxies, as predicted e.g., by the in-situ scenario. Four objects show some signatures of a forthcoming/ongoing AGN feedback, that is thought to trigger the morphological transition from star-forming disks to ETGs.},
